ume, a multi-disciplinary group of scholars provides alternative approaches to understanding the period. Addressing developments in governance, ceremony, literature, art, music, clerical education and the city's very sense of its own identity, the essays examine how a variety of actors, from poets to popes, addressed the intermittent crises and shifting dynamics of these centuries with creative solutions that bolstered the city's resilience. Without denying that the past (both pre-Christian and Christian) always remained a powerful touchstone, the studies in this volume offer rich new insights into the myriad ways that Rome and Romans, between the fifth and the eleventh centuries, creatively assimilated the past in order to shape the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCity planningxHistoryyTo 1500zItalyzRome. 0aCommunity development, UrbanzItalyzRomexHistoryy476-1420. 0aCommunity development, UrbanzItalyzRomexHistoryyDomitian, 81-96. 4aAntiquity. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aSociology and Social History. 4aUrban Cultures. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh  aRome - Middle Ages, Rome - Late Antiquity, History - Rome (312-1300), Cultural geography - Rome.1 aDijk, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDijk, Ann, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKalas, Gregor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKalas, Gregor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKinney, Dale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLatham, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNardini, Luisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorth, William, econtributor.4ctb4https: